name: sfchronicle
text:
East Bay native G-Eazy is among the featured performers for this weekend’s Save Our Stages festival, a three-day virtual concert raising money for independent music venues in the Bay Area and across the nation shuttered during the coronavirus pandemic. 
https://t.co/Kq4RrHdM1h

name: sfchronicle
text:
Columnist @Bruce_Jenkins1 votes for Oakland-raised Joe Morgan, who died Sunday, as the greatest second baseman of all time. 

"Put together everything Morgan offered on a baseball field, and nobody else measures up," he writes. 

https://t.co/EadcPmauCq

name: sfchronicle
text:
The idea is to make schools more racially and economically integrated while simplifying a complicated process.

Instead of having a choice of 112 kindergarten programs, a family would be able to choose within a so-called zone near where they live.

name: sfchronicle
text:
If proposed cost cutting measures don’t fill the budget shortfall, BART could announce layoffs in December, to take effect in February.

“That is only as a last resort,” BART General Manager Bob Powers told The Chronicle Friday.

https://t.co/LGjjtQEzvO

text:
Mayor London Breed calls a proposal to force 44 San Francisco public schools to change their names an “offensive” waste of time, energy and resources from a district that still has no date to bring kids back to the classroom.

name: sfchronicle
text:
San Rafael police arrested a man they say stole a truck — and now he’s wanted for the theft of Maki, the San Francisco Zoo lemur, after officers said they discovered photos of the endangered animal on his cell phone.

https://t.co/NIWrrQRnVv

name: sfchronicle
text:
Multiple Bay Area cities break or tie daily record high temperatures: 

- Napa ties record of 97 degrees
- Richmond ties record of 95 degrees
- S.F. breaks 1988 record with 92 degrees
- Oakland breaks 1974 record with 94 degrees 

https://t.co/Z1io6Ea40g

name: sfchronicle
text:
PG&E has restored power to "essentially all" homes and businesses that had their electricity cut in recent days as a safety precaution ahead of gusty winds and the heightened fire risk that came with them, the company said.

https://t.co/c3oSrskspZ

text:
More than a third of S.F.'s 125 schools made the list of "inappropriate names" — including Balboa, Lowell and Mission high schools, as well as Roosevelt and Presidio middle schools.

Vote: Which school names would you choose to change?
